==Old English==

===Etymology===
Common Germanic, from Indo-European ''*septṃ'' ‘seven’.  Cognate with Old High German [[sibun]] (German [[sieben]]), Old Saxon ''siƀun'' (Dutch [[zeven]]), Old Norse [[sjau]] (Swedish [[sju]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌹𐌱𐌿𐌽]]; and, outside the Germanic languages, with Sanskrit [[सप्त]], Greek [[ἑπτά]], Latin [[septem]] (French [[sept]] etc.), Albanian [[shtatë]], Old Irish [[secht]] (Irish [[seacht]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'seovon/

===Noun===
'''seofon''' (ordinal: '''seofoþa''')
# [[seven]], [[7]]

